  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **a felony** in most jurisdictions, including the United States. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. Money laundering is considered a serious criminal offense because it enables criminal activity to continue and undermines the integrity of financial systems.\n\n### **Key Points:**\n1. **Federal Law (U.S.):** Under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957), money laundering is a federal crime. Penalties can include:\n   - Up to **20 years in prison**.\n   - Fines of up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater.\n   - Forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n\n2. **State Laws:** Many states also have their own money laundering laws, and penalties can vary depending on the state and the amount of money involved.\n\n3. **International Context:** Money laundering is also a crime in most countries and is often prosecuted under laws aligned with international agreements like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** recommendations.\n\n4. **Associated Crimes:** Money laundering is often linked to other serious crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, terrorism financing, and organized crime, which can result in additional charges and harsher penalties.\n\nIf you suspect or are involved in a situation related to money laundering, it\u2019s critical to consult a qualified attorney to understand your rights and legal options.",
